What is a Silicon Anode Battery?
Silicon anode batteries employ nano‑engineered silicon particles, silicon‑carbon composites, or silicon‑graphite hybrids as the negative electrode. The high lithium‑storage capacity of silicon is offset by its substantial volume expansion (up to 300 %) during lithiation, which historically caused rapid capacity fade. Recent advances in nanostructuring, binder chemistries, and artificial solid‑electrolyte interphase (SEI) stabilizers have mitigated these issues, delivering cycle lives exceeding 1,000 cycles with minimal degradation. These technological breakthroughs have moved silicon anodes from laboratory prototypes to commercially viable solutions for high‑capacity stationary storage systems.
